[2] Germany (Munich): wastewater
Date: Tue 21 Dec 2021
Source: DETV [edited]
https://detv.us/2021/12/21/more-widespread-than-expected-omikron-discovered-in-munich-wastewater/


The new omicron variant of the coronavirus has been detectable in Munich wastewater for 2 weeks -- and is therefore probably more widespread than previously thought. When examining the wastewater, the variant was detected from 7 Dec 2021, announced the Munich University Clinic as a result of the regular monitoring, which has been analyzing samples from the Munich sewerage system only once a week since April 2020 and now twice a week.

In the latest results, which were available on Monday [20 Dec 2021], wastewater samples from 4 locations in Munich and from a sewage treatment plant were analyzed up to 10 Dec 2021. The researchers found traces of the variant in 5 of 6 samples. "This indicates that the spread of this virus variant in Munich was already greater in calendar week 49 than previously assumed," explained project manager Andreas Wieser from the Tropical Institute. The sequences of strains of the delta variant were still dominant. In the samples previously analyzed up to 3 Dec 2021, there was no evidence of the omicron variant.

The wastewater monitoring in Munich, which began at the beginning of the pandemic, is one of the 1st and longest investigations to track the viral load in wastewater worldwide. Background: Several days often pass between the increase in new infections and the official number of reports, so that the dynamics of the pandemic and the spread of new variants can be identified faster and more effectively using the wastewater analyses.

--
Communicated by:
Mary Marshall
<mjm2020@googlemail.com>

[Thanks to Sabine Zentis for the weblink.

"Experience with other viral diseases [and now SARS-CoV-2] has shown that monitoring sewage for traces of a pathogen enables effective surveillance of entire communities, providing a sensitive signal of whether the pathogen is present in the population and whether transmission is increasing or declining. Researchers around the world are now pursuing the same approach for COVID-19 with the hope that wastewater data can supplement current measures of its prevalence.... [Wastewater results] could facilitate social distancing interventions before community transmission reaches exponential growth" (https://www.nature.com/articles/s41587-020-0690-1). - Mod.LK]

